<TEXT>
<P>
Tens of thousands of Hungarians took to the streets in Budapest to celebrate 
new freedoms in one of the largest displays of nationalist sentiment since the 
anti-Soviet uprising in 1956. It was the first time in 41 years that Communist 
officials had made a public legal holiday of the March 15 anniversary of 
Hungary's unsuccessful revolt against Austria in 1848. A 12-point declaration 
calling for more freedom and independence was read at a large rally in front of 
the Hungarian state television offices. The declaration also demanded the 
withdrawal of Soviet troops, a multi-party political system and freedom of 
speech and the press. 
